So let's first find the length of segment $AD$. Since $ABCD$ is a square and $AE$ is perpendicular to $ED$, we can see that triangle $AED$ is a right triangle with legs $AE$ and $DE$. We can use the Pythagorean Theorem to find the length of the hypotenuse $AD$:
\begin{align*}
AE^2 + DE^2 &= AD^2\\
8^2 + 6^2 &= AD^2\\
64 + 36 &= AD^2\\
100 &= AD^2\\
AD &= \sqrt{100}\\
AD &= 10
\end{align*}
Since $ABCD$ is a square, we know that all sides are equal in length. Therefore, the length of segment $AD$ is equal to the length of segment $BC$. This means that:
\begin{align*}
BC &= AD\\
BC &= 10
\end{align*}
Now that we know the length of segment $AD$ and the length of segment $BC$, we can find the area of pentagon $AEDCB$. The area of pentagon $AEDCB$ is equal to the area of square $ABCD$ minus the area of triangle $AED$. The area of square $ABCD$ is equal to the length of one side squared, so:
\begin{align*}
\text{Area of square }ABCD &= 10^2\\
&= \boxed{100}
\end{align*}
The area of triangle $AED$ is equal to half of the product of the lengths of its legs, so:
\begin{align*}
\text{Area of triangle }AED &= \frac{1}{2} \cdot 8 \cdot 6\\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot 48\\
&= \boxed{24}
\end{align*}
To find the area of pentagon $AEDCB$, we subtract the area of triangle $AED$ from the area of square $ABCD$:
\begin{align*}
\text{Area of pentagon }AEDCB &= \text{Area of square }ABCD - \text{Area of triangle }AED\\
&= 100 - 24\\
&= \boxed{76}
\end{align*}
Therefore, the area of pentagon $AEDCB$ is $\boxed{76}$ square units.

